{"parse":{"title":"look","pageid":5673,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|löök|Look}}\n==English==\n{{wp|,+ing}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|en|:inh|enm:loken|tree=1}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|loken}}, {{m|enm|lokien}}, from {{inh|en|ang|lōcian}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*lōkōn}}. Further origin {{unk|en|title=unknown}}, no certain cognates outside Germanic.<ref>{{R:Philippa EWN 2009|look}}</ref> Cognate with {{cog|sco|luke}}, {{m|sco|luik}}, {{m|sco|leuk|t=to look, see}}, {{cog|fy|lôkje}}, {{m|fy|loaitsje|t=to look}}, {{cog|nl|loeken|t=to look}}, {{cog|nds-de|löken}}. Likely also related to {{cog|de|lugen|t=to peek}}, {{cog|gsw|luege|t=to look}}, {{cog|yi|לוגן}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|lo͝ok}}, {{IPA|en|/lʊk/}}\n** {{IPA|en|[lɵk]|a=SSB}}\n*** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-look.wav|a=Southern England|IPA=[lɵk]}}\n** {{homophones|en|luck<aa:most of <<Northern England>>>}}\n* {{IPA|en|/luːk/<aa:some <<Northern Enɡlish>> dialects, esp. Bolton, <<Geordie>>>}} {{q|formerly more widespread}}<ref>{{R:Critical Pronouncing Dictionary|Look|351|2|ipage=1}}</ref>\n** {{IPA|en|[luːx]<aa:<<Liverpool>> variant>}}\n** {{homophones|en|Luke}}\n* {{IPA|en|/lʉk/|a=MLE,Scotland,Northern Ireland}}\n** {{homophones|en|Luke<aa:Scotland,NI>}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ʊk|uːk|s=1}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# To [[try]] to [[see]], to [[pay attention]] to with one’s [[eyes]].\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:look}}\n## {{lb|en|intransitive}} {{non-gloss|As an intransitive verb, often with \"at\".}}\n##: {{troponyms|en|glance|Thesaurus:stare}}\n##: {{ux|en|They kept '''looking''' at me.}}\n##: {{ux|en|Don’t '''look''' in the closet.}}\n##* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=5|passage=Then came a maid with hand-bag and shawls, and after her a tall young lady.{{...}}She '''looked''' around expectantly, and recognizing Mrs. Cooke's maid{{...}}Miss Thorn greeted her with a smile which greatly prepossessed us in her favor.}}\n##* {{RQ:Maxwell Mirror and the Lamp|chapter=10|passage=He '''looked''' round the poor room, at the distempered walls, and the bad engravings in meretricious frames, the crinkly paper and wax flowers on the chiffonier; and he thought of a room like Father Bryan's, with panelling, with cut glass, with tulips in silver pots, such a room as he had hoped to have for his own.}}\n##* {{quote-song|en|year=1968|author=Ray Thomas|title=Legend of a Mind|artist=The Moody Blues|album=In Search of the Lost Chord|passage=Timothy Leary's dead. <br> No, no no no, he's outside, '''looking''' in.}}\n## {{lb|en|transitive|colloquial}} {{non-gloss|As a transitive verb, often in the {{glossary|imperative mood|imperative}}; chiefly takes {{glossary|relative clause}} as direct object.}}\n##: {{ux|en|'''Look''' what you did to him!}}\n##: {{ux|en|'''Look''' who's back!}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1972|title=w:The Godfather|passage='''Look''' how they massacred my boy.}}\n# {{senseid|en|appear}} To [[appear]], to [[seem]].\n#: {{ux|en|It '''looks''' as if it’s going to rain soon. ''or'' It '''looks''' like it’s going to rain soon. ''or'' It looks like rain [is coming].}}\n#: {{ux|en|Our new boss '''looks''' to be friendly.}}\n#: {{ux|en|It '''looks''' as if [''or'' like] I'm stuck with you.}}\n#: {{ux|en|You didn't use to '''look''' so dismal, but now you '''look'''/are '''look'''ing positively unhappy.}}\n#: {{ux|en|{{q|UK}} He always '''looks''' like scoring a goal if not two.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=c. 1701-03|author=w:Joseph Addison|url=http://books.google.com.au/books?id=HoUTAAAAQAAJ|title=Remarks on Several Parts of Italy, &amp;c.|publisher=Dedication\n|passage=THERE is a pleaſure in owning obligations which it is a pleaſure to have received; but ſhould I publiſh any favours done me by your Lordſhip, I am afraid it would '''look''' more like vanity, than gratitude.}}\n#* {{RQ:Ferguson Zollenstein|IV\n|passage=So this was my future home, I thought!{{...}}Backed by towering hills, the but faintly discernible purple line of the French boundary off to the southwest, a sky of palest Gobelin flecked with fat, fleecy little clouds, it in truth '''looked''' a dear little city; the city of one's dreams.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1950|month=April|author=Timothy H. Cobb|title=The Kenya-Uganda Railway|journal=Railway Magazine|pages=264-265|text=You wake up next morning on what '''looks''' like Salisbury Plain, only here you climb up the side of every combe, round the end and out the other side.}}\n#* {{RQ:Williams Velveteen Rabbit|passage=He loved him so hard that he loved all his whiskers off, and the pink lining to his ears turned grey, and his brown spots faded. He even began to lose his shape, and he scarcely '''looked''' like a rabbit any more, except to the Boy.}}\n#* {{RQ:Allingham China Governess|chapter=2|passage=Now that she had rested and had fed from the luncheon tray Mrs. Broome had just removed, she had reverted to her normal gaiety.&nbsp; She '''looked''' cool in a grey tailored cotton dress with a terracotta scarf and shoes and her hair a black silk helmet.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=September 18, 2011|author=Ben Dirs|work=BBC Sport| title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/14959055.stm Rugby World Cup 2011: England 41-10 Georgia]| passage=And when scrum-half Ben Youngs, who had a poor game, was burgled by opposite number Irakli Abuseridze and the ball shipped down the line to Irakli Machkhaneli, it '''looked''' like Georgia had scored a try of their own, but the winger's foot was in touch.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2012|title=Chelsea 6-0 Wolves|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19632463\n|passage=Chelsea's youngsters, who '''looked''' lively throughout, then combined for the second goal in the seventh minute. Romeu's shot was saved by Wolves goalkeeper Dorus De Vries but Piazon kept the ball alive and turned it back for an unmarked Bertrand to blast home.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-08|volume=407|issue=8839|page=52|magazine=w:The Economist| title=[http://www.economist.com/news/international/21579039-chinas-growing-empire-ports-abroad-mainly-about-trade-not-aggression-new-masters The new masters and commanders]| passage=From the ground, Colombo’s port does not '''look''' like much. Those entering it are greeted by wire fences, walls dating back to colonial times and security posts. For mariners leaving the port after lonely nights on the high seas, the delights of the B52 Night Club and Stallion Pub lie a stumble away.}}\n# {{lb|en|copulative}} To give an appearance of being.\n#: {{ux|en|That painting '''looks''' nice.}}\n#: {{ux|en|You’re '''looking''' worried. Whaddya thinking about?}}\n#: {{ux|en|You '''looked''' a fool when you slipped on a banana peel.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1843|author=w:Thomas Carlyle|title=[[:w:Past and Present (book)|Past and Present]]|section=book 2, chapter 6, ''Monk Samson''|passage=Once, slipping the money clandestinely, just in the act of taking leave, he slipt it not into her hand but on the floor, and another had it; whereupon the poor Monk, coming to know it, '''looked''' mere despair for some days{{nb...}}.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|often|with \"for\"}} To [[search]] for, to [[try]] to [[find]].\n# To face or present a view.\n#: {{ux|en|The hotel '''looks''' over the valleys of the Hindu Kush.}}\n#* '''1769''', {{w|Benjamin Blayney}} (editor), ''{{w|King James Version|King James Bible}}'', Oxford standard text, ''[[s:Bible (King James)/Ezekiel|Ezekiel]]'', xi, 1,\n#*: Moreover the spirit lifted me up, and brought me unto the east gate of the LORD's house, which '''looketh''' eastward:\n#* {{RQ:Dunsany Pegana\n|passage=Wornath-Mavai lieth in a valley and '''looketh''' towards the south, and on the slopes of it Sish rested among the flowers when Sish was young.}}\n# To expect or anticipate.\n#: {{ux|en|I '''look''' to each hour for my lover’s arrival.}}\n#* '''1596''', {{w|Edmund Spenser}}, ''{{w|The Fairie Queene}}'', Book VI, Canto XI, '''1750''', ''The Works of Edmund Spenser'', Volume 4, [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=PyxMAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA139&dq=%22looking+each+hour+into+death%27s+mouth+to+fall%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjTjumR2vLZAhVSOZAKHTDnBAMQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=%22looking%20each%20hour%20into%20death's%20mouth%20to%20fall%22&f=false page 139],\n#* {{RQ:Noire Thug-A-Licious|page=108|passage=\"Ain't gone be no Rikers Island for you next time,\" I warned him. \"You get tapped on another gun charge and you '''looking''' at some upstate time.\"<br>'''Looking''' each Hour into Death's Mouth to fall,}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-1|1|1|passage=Gloster, what ere we like, thou art Protector,<br>And '''lookest''' to command the Prince and Realme.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[express]] or [[manifest]] by a look.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=c. 1815|author=w:Lord Byron|title=Waterloo\n|passage=Soft eyes '''looked''' love to eyes which spake again,}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1923|author=Ernest Bramah|title=The Eyes of Max Carrados\n|passage=For a few seconds Mr Carlyle '''looked''' his unutterable feelings. When he did speak it was with crushing deliberation.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|often|with \"to\"}} To make sure of, to see to.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1898|translator=w:Samuel Butler|author=w:Homer|title=[[s:The Odyssey (Butler)/Book XXIII|The Odyssey]]\n|passage=\"'''Look''' to it yourself, father,\" answered Telemachus, \"for they say you are the wisest counsellor in the world, and that there is no other mortal man who can compare with you.{{nb...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|dated|sometimes|figurative}} To show oneself in looking; to [[peep out]].\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Taming of the Shrew|Induction|2|text=I have{{...}}more feet than shoes, or such shoes as my toes '''look''' through the overleather.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic|_|or|_|dialectal}} To [[check#Verb|check]], to [[make sure#Verb|make sure]] (of something).\n#* {{RQ:Swift Gulliver|part=II|page=151|passage=Finding it was like to overblow, we took in our Sprit-ſail, and ſtood by to hand the Fore-ſail; but making foul Weather, we '''look'd''' the Guns were all faſt, and handed the Miſſen.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To look at; to turn the eyes toward.\n#* {{RQ:Hough Purchase Price|chapter=I|text=Serene, smiling, enigmatic, she faced him with no fear whatever showing in her dark eyes.{{...}}She put back a truant curl from her forehead where it had sought egress to the world, and '''looked''' him full in the face now,{{nb...}}.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[seek]]; to search for.\n#* {{circa|1552–1599}}, {{w|Edmund Spenser}}, unidentified sonnet,\n#*: '''Looking''' my love, I go from place to place, <br> Like a young fawn that late hath lost the hind; <br> And seek each where, where last I saw her face, <br> Whose image yet I carry fresh in mind.\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To influence, overawe, or subdue by looks or presence.\n#: {{ux|en|to '''look''' down opposition}}\n#* '''1692''', {{w|John Dryden}}, ''Cleomenes the Spartan Hero, a Tragedy'', Act 3, Scene 1, '''1701''', ''The Comedies, Tragedies, and Operas Written by John Dryden, Esq'', Volume 2, [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=zehWAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA1-PA464&dq=%22A+spirit+fit+to+start+into+an+empire,+And+look+the+world+to+law.%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiwjsH0nvPZAhWHqJQKHacPACsQ6AEITTAH#v=onepage&q=%22A%20spirit%20fit%20to%20start%20into%20an%20empire%2C%20And%20look%20the%20world%20to%20law.%22&f=false page 464],\n#*: A Spirit fit to start into an Empire, <br> And '''look''' the World to Law.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1882|author=w:Wilkie Collins|title=Heart and Science\n|passage=Ovid might have evaded her entreaties by means of an excuse. But her eyes were irresistible: they '''looked''' him into submission in an instant.}}\n# {{senseid|en|baseball}}{{lb|en|baseball}} To [[look at]] a pitch as a batter without swinging at it.\n#: {{ux|en|The fastball caught him '''looking.'''}}\n#: {{ux|en|Clem Labine struck Mays out '''looking''' at his last at bat.}}\n#: {{ux|en|It's unusual for Mays to strike out '''looking'''. He usually takes a cut at it.}}\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{en-conj|old=1}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|en|title=phrasal verbs derived from ''look (verb)''\n|look about\n|look after\n|look around\n|look at\n|look at me,look-at-me\n|look away\n|look back\n|look down\n|look down on\n|look down upon\n|look for\n|look forward\n|look forward to\n|look in on\n|look into\n|look it\n|look on\n|look out\n|look out for\n|look over\n|look past\n|look round\n|look through\n|look to\n|look up\n|look up to\n|look upon\n|look ahead|look ahead to}}\n\n{{col3|en|title=other terms derived from ''look (verb)''\n|belook|look on the black side|look on the bright side of it|look on the dark side|look on the dark side of it|look on the gloomy side|look on the positive side\n|forelook\n|lookalike,look-alike\n|look alive\n|lookee\n|looker\n|lookit\n|look lively\n|lookout,look-out\n|look-see\n|look before you leap|look ahere\n|look down one's nose\n|look daggers\n|look here|look at it this way\n|look oneself| look both ways|look what the wind blew in|what am I looking at\n|look sharp\n|look someone in the eye\n|look the other way\n|look what the cat's brought in\n|mislook\n|onlooker|look a fright|lookability|lookable|uplook\n|outlook\n|overlook\n|relook\n|underlook|look like who did it and ran away\n|a cat can look at a king|a cat may look at a king|as soon as look at someone|does someone look like|don't look a gift horse in the mouth|don't look at me|look alike|look as if one had lost a shilling and found sixpence|look as if one has been dragged through a hedge backwards|look as if one has lost a shilling and found sixpence|look at oneself in the mirror|look at you|look before one leaps|look beyond|look beyond the end of one's nose|look beyond the tip of one's nose|look for a dog to kick|look for number one|look for trouble|look in the face|look like|look like a bomb has hit it|look like something the cat brought in|look like something the cat dragged in|look like something the cat's dragged in|look like who did it and ran|look off|look on as|look on the bright side|look one's age|look one's best|look out for number one|look out for Number One|look over one's shoulder|look past the end of one's nose|look past the tip of one's nose|look the part|look through rose-colored glasses|look through rose-tinted glasses|look under rocks|look up and down|look what the cat dragged in|look what the cat drug in|look what the cat's dragged in|look who the cat dragged in|look who's talking|look you|look-out book|made you look|never look a gift horse in the mouth|not look a day over|not much to look at|you don't look at the mantelpiece when you poke the fire|you don't look at the mantelpiece when you're poking the fire|don't look now|look like one swallowed a bug|look shy|look snappy|look-at-me|no-look| outward-looking}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desctree|srn|luku}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|to try to see}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|kyk}}\n* Ainu: {{tt|ain|inkar}}, {{tt|ain|インカㇽ|tr=inkar}}\n* Akatek: {{tt|knj|il}}\n* Albanian: {{tt+|sq|shoh}}, {{tt+|sq|shikoj}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{tt|alt|багар}}, {{tt|alt|караар}}\n* Arabic: {{tt+|ar|نَظَرَ}}, {{tt|ar|شاف|tr=šāf}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|بص|tr=baṣṣ}}, {{tt|arz|شاف|tr=šāf}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{tt|acw|طالع|tr=ṭālaʕ}}, {{tt|acw|اتفَرَّج|tr=atfarraj}}, {{tt|acw|شاف|tr=šāf}}\n*: North Levantine Arabic: {{tt|ajp|تطلّع|tr=tṭallaʕ}}, {{tt|ajp|تفرّج|tr=tfarraj}}, {{tt|arz|شاف|tr=šāf}}\n*: South Levantine Arabic: {{tt|ajp|تطلّع|tr=tṭallaʕ}}, {{tt|ajp|تفرّج|tr=tfarraj}}, {{tt|arz|شاف|tr=šāf}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|նայել}}, {{t+|hy|դիտել}}\n* Assamese: {{tt|as|চা}}\n* Asturian: {{tt|ast|mirar}}, {{tt|ast|amirar}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{tt+|az|baxmaq}}\n* Bakhtiari: {{tt|bqi|نیشتن|tr=niyašten}}\n* Bangi: {{t|bni|keka}}, {{t|bni|tala}}\n* Bashkir: {{tt|ba|ҡарау}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt+|be|глядзе́ць|impf}}, {{tt|be|паглядзе́ць|pf}}\n* Bengali: {{tt|bn|তাকান}}\n* Breton: {{tt+|br|sellout}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|гле́дам|impf}}\n* Burmese: {{tt+|my|ကြည့်}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|mirar}}, {{tt+|ca|guaitar}}\n* Chechen: {{tt|ce|хьажа}}\n* Chin:\n*: Tedim Chin: {{tt|ctd|en}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt+|yue|睇|tr=tai2}}, {{tt|yue|望|tr=mong6}}\n*: Dungan: {{tt|dng|кан}}\n*: Hokkien: {{tt+|nan-hbl|看|tr=khòaⁿ, khàn}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|看|tr=kàn}}, {{tt+|cmn|視|tr=shì}} {{qualifier|literary}}, {{tt+|cmn|見|tr=jiàn}} {{qualifier|literary or in compounds}}\n*: Wu: {{tt|wuu|看}}\n* Chinook Jargon: {{t|chn|nanich}}\n* Czech: {{tt|cs|dívat|impf|alt=dívat se}}, {{tt|cs|podívat|pf|alt=podívat se}}\n* Danish: {{tt|da|kigge}}, {{tt|da|kikke}}, {{tt+|da|se}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|kijken}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|rigardi}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|vaatama}}\n* Ewe: {{tt|ee|kpɔ}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|líta}}, {{tt|fo|hyggja}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|katsoa}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|regarder}}\n* Frisian:\n*: North Frisian: {{tt|frr|kiike}}\n* Friulian: {{tt|fur|vuardâ}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|mirar}}\n* Ge'ez: {{tt|gez|ነጸረ}}\n* Georgian: {{tt|ka|ყურება}}, {{tt|ka|ცქერა}}, {{tt|ka|ჭვრეტა}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|sehen}}, {{tt+|de|schauen}}, {{tt+|de|blicken}}, {{tt+|de|hinschauen}}, {{tt+|de|hinsehen}}, {{qualifier|colloquial}} {{tt+|de|gucken}}, {{tt|de|guggen}}, {{qualifier|rarely}} {{tt+|de|kucken}}, {{tt+|de|ansehen}}\n*: Alemannic German: {{tt|gsw|luege}}\n* Gothic: {{tt|got|𐌰𐍄𐍃𐌰𐌹𐍈𐌰𐌽}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|κοιτάζω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{tt|grc|σκοπέω}}, {{qualifier|Epic}} {{tt|grc|λεύσσω}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Paraguayan Guarani: {{tt-check|gug|ma'ẽ}}\n* Gujarati: {{tt|gu|જોવું}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|הִסְתַּכֵּל|tr=histakél}}, {{tt+|he|הביט|tr=hibít}}, {{tt+|he|ראה|tr=ra'á}}\n* Hindi: {{tt+|hi|देखना}}, {{tt|hi|निगाह करना}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|néz}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt|is|kíkja}}, {{tt+|is|horfa}}, {{tt+|is|sjá}}, {{tt|is|líta}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|regardar}}\n* Indonesian: {{t|id|pandangi}}\n* Ingush: {{tt|inh|хьежа}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt|ia|reguardar}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|amharc}}, {{tt|ga|féach}}\n* Istriot: {{tt|ist|vardà}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|guardare}}\n* Jamaican Creole: {{tt|jam|coo}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|見る|tr=みる, miru}} (''also:'' to [[see]]), {{tt+|ja|観る|tr=みる, miru}} (''actively''), {{tt|ja|見てみる|tr=mitemiru}}, {{tt|ja|ご覧|tr=ごらんになる, go-ran ni naru|alt=ご覧になる}} {{qualifier|honorific}}, {{tt+|ja|拝見|alt=拝見する|tr=はいけんする, haiken surú}} {{qualifier|humble}}\n* Kabuverdianu: {{tt|kea|djobe}}, {{tt|kea|odja}}, {{tt|kea|oiá}}\n* Kazakh: {{tt+|kk|қарау}}\n* Khmer: {{tt+|km|មើល}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|보다}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{tt|ckb|تەمەشاکردن}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{tt|ky|кара-}}\n* Lao: {{tt|lo|ເບິ່ງ}}\n* Latgalian: {{tt|ltg|vērtīs}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|specto}}, {{tt+|la|video}}, {{tt|la|tueor}}, {{tt|la|obtueor}}\n* Latvian: {{tt|lv|skats}}\n* Lingala: {{t|ln|keka}}, {{t|ln|tala}}\n* Lithuanian: {{tt+|lt|žiūrėti}}\n* Lombard: {{tt+|lmo|vardà}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|гледа|impf}}\n* Malayalam: {{tt+|ml|നോക്കുക}}\n* Manchu: {{tt|mnc|ᡨᡠᠸᠠᠮᠪᡳ}}\n* Māori: {{tt|mi|titiro}}, {{tt|mi|tiro hura}} {{qualifier|look sideways}}\n* Marathi: {{t+|mr|बघणे}}\n* Miwok:\n*: Southern Sierra Miwok: {{tt|skd|hyk·eʔ jo·ʔun}}\n* Mongolian: {{tt+|mn|харах}}\n* Naga:\n*: Khiamniungan Naga: {{t|kix|thāp}}\n* Neapolitan: {{tt|nap|guardà}}\n* Nivkh: {{tt|niv|нюдь}}\n* Norman: {{tt|nrf|r'garder}}\n* Norwegian: {{tt+|no|se}}, {{tt|no|skue}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|lita}}\n* Occitan: {{tt+|oc|gaitar}}\n* Ojibwe: {{tt|oj|nandawaabam}}\n* Old English: {{tt|ang|lōcian}}\n* Old Norse: {{tt|non|sjá}}, {{tt|non|sēa}}, {{tt|non|líta}}\n* Old Saxon: {{tt|osx|lokon}}\n* Persian:\n*: Dari: {{t|fa|سیل کردن|tr=sayl kardan}}, {{tt+|fa|نگاه کردن|tr=nigāh kardan}}, {{tt+|fa|نگریستن|tr=nigarīstan}}\n*: Iranian Persian: {{tt+|fa|نگاه کردن|tr=negâh kardan}}, {{tt+|fa|نگریستن|tr=negaristan}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|patrzeć|impf}}, {{tt+|pl|popatrzeć|pf}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|olhar}}\n* Quechua: {{tt|qu|qhaway}}\n* Rapa Nui: {{tt|rap|ki}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|privi}}, {{tt+|ro|uita}}, {{tt+|ro